# Fluff Date: 2026-02-19 16:29:24
overview:<p>The Scarecrow is a rare, mixed-technology medium BattleMech introduced in 3099 by Corean Enterprises at their Augusta facility. Designed exclusively for the Armed Forces of the Federated Suns, the Scarecrow was purpose-built for a single grim mission: the eradication of enemy infantry. Incorporating both Clan and Inner Sphere technology, including Clan-specification weapons manufactured under license by Corean and General Motors, the design represents a deliberate and controversial approach to anti-infantry warfare. The AFFS officially denied the existence of the Scarecrow for decades, only publicly acknowledging its deployment in the 3140s. Few Scarecrows are known to exist, and the design has never been observed outside Federated Suns service.</p>

capabilities:<p>Built on a Corean Model 000 endo-composite chassis and powered by a GM 200 XL engine, the Scarecrow achieves a top speed of 86 kph, supplemented by three Rawlings 80 jump jets providing 90 meters of jump capability. While not fast by medium BattleMech standards, the Scarecrow is more than quick enough to run down any conventional infantry formation. A compact gyroscope frees internal volume for the design's extensive weapons suite and electronic warfare systems.</p><p>The Scarecrow carries an impressive anti-infantry arsenal. Three ExoStar Pinnacle Clan-specification extended-range medium lasers provide accurate fire at range, while two Omicron 950 medium pulse lasers deliver punishing close-range salvos. Eight GM Ultralight Clan light machine guns, paired in two Corean Bulletstorm machine gun arrays, shred unarmored infantry with devastating efficiency. Two Zippo Longtorch extended-range flamers flush entrenched troops from cover, and two Federated Mantrap anti-battle armor pods ensure even armored infantry cannot safely close. Eight tons of StarGuard III armor with CASE II protection provides adequate survivability, while a Chameleon Light Polarization Shield and Bloodhound Active Probe allow the Scarecrow to hunt its prey undetected.</p>

deployment:<p>Known by the unflattering nickname "Hobbled Scarecrow," the UCU-F4r strips the Chameleon Light Polarization Shield and machine gun arrays from the base design, replacing them with three standard medium lasers. This modification was intended to give the Scarecrow some measure of effectiveness against other BattleMechs. In practice, however, the thin armor and limited speed that are acceptable in an infantry hunter prove serious liabilities in mech-on-mech engagements, leaving the Hobbled Scarecrow easy prey for all but the lightest opponents. The variant often arises from necessity rather than preference, as field units lacking replacement parts for the specialized Chameleon system convert their Scarecrows to this more maintainable configuration.</p>

history:<p>The Scarecrow emerged from a classified Corean Enterprises program in the late thirty-first century, entering production in 3099. The AFFS deliberately kept the design secret, officially denying its existence for over four decades. This secrecy reflected the political sensitivity surrounding a BattleMech designed explicitly to kill infantry, a role that attracted criticism from humanitarian organizations and foreign governments alike.</p><p>The most storied, if unverified, deployment of the Scarecrow took place on McComb over a fifteen-year period. Draconis Combine Mustered Soldiery infantrymen deployed to raid the world propagated the legend of the Dragon of Gorman Heights, a spectral figure of fire and steel said to appear and annihilate entire platoons of foot soldiers. While never officially confirmed, most analysts believe repeated Scarecrow deployments designed to attack DCMS infantry on a psychological scale reinforced this legend.</p><p>When the AFFS finally acknowledged the Scarecrow in 3140, humanitarian agencies condemned its deployment, arguing that a BattleMech designed solely to kill infantry crossed ethical boundaries. The AFFS largely dismissed these complaints, with defenders of the program citing the long history of anti-infantry designs stretching back to machines like the Piranha and the Stinger. Reports place Scarecrows along the Periphery March border, suggesting the AFFS intends to use them to dissuade pirate attacks, though the pressures of Capellan and Combine incursions make broader deployment likely only a matter of time.</p>

